body:
Hmm... I just finished implementing it the verbose way...
But what you're saying makes sense, I didn't think of that... I'll look into it after the holidays. I think converting the linear index to line+column+file is pretty straight-forward, no need to provide a Python function to do it (where would you put it?). I would just describe the linear index in the `--json` switch documentation.

What do you think about storing the pointer to LocationManager and setting it in the constructor like this:
```cpp
template <class Struct>
class JsonBaseVisitor : public BaseVisitor<Struct>
{
private:
    Struct& self() { return static_cast<Struct&>(*this); }
public:
    std::string s, indtd = "";
    int indent_level = 0, indent_spaces = 4;
    LocationManager* lm = nullptr;
public:
    JsonBaseVisitor(LocationManager &lmref) {
        lm = &lmref;
        s.reserve(100000);
    }
// ...
```
?

In terms of readability, I think it's better than the alternative - passing `lm` to all the Visitors and their visit functions, but I also don't like it, because the lifetime of a JsonBaseVisitor can be different than that of an AST passed to visit_ast().
If JsonBaseVisitor ever gets reused for a different AST, it could happen to be using an non-relevant LocationManager, which would be an annoying thing to debug.
I'm not sure which is better.
